hydiomatic.macros: Simplify defrules

With this change, defrules will natively understand two styles of rules:

 [[fresh-vars] `(pattern) `(substitute)]

...and:

 [(some-expression ...)]

If the first value in the rule definition is a HyExpression, the rule
will be returned as-is. Otherwise, it will be treated as if the contents
were parameters for the old (rule) function. The old (rule) function is
gone, and is replaced by a new one used by the defrules macro
internally.

Signed-off-by: Gergely Nagy <algernon@balabit.hu>

the calls.

hydiomatic.macros: Simplify the defrules syntax

Instead of requiring every rule to either specify the list of fresh
LVars as its first argument, or have a single HyExpression within the
rule definition list, extract the used LVars automatically, and if the
rule definition is not a list, turn it into one without further
processing.

This means that rules can use ?x LVars, and these will automatically
be (fresh)'d, without the need to specifiy them up front. Also, rules
that need more work than this, can be specified bare, no need to wrap
them in a one-element list.

Signed-off-by: Gergely Nagy <algernon@madhouse-project.org>

hydiomatic.rules: Start adding rules for the Grand Cleanup

This introduces a rather ugly hack: a set of rules will be run after
simplification to clean up temporary renames. The reason we do this, is
because we want to skip applying some rules over and over again: so we
transform the expression so that the rule doesn't recognise it
anymore. But in the end, we want to transform it back. The old functions
that do no cleanup are available under a starred name.

The new rules - not part of the default set - suggest modifications that
follow the Grand Language Cleanup.

Updates for recent Hy changes

Beyond simple syntax and function signature updates, the biggest changes are in
the handling/use of--the now missing--`cons`.

Also, some rules have been added that reflect these Hy language changes, as
well.  They still need tests.  A particularly good test/demo could involve the
automatic application of these very changes!  Perhaps only a subset could be
reasonably performed, since some changes (e.g. the "lifting"/pulling out of
`cons`es from quoted forms) aren't part of the current rulesets.  We might be
able to add them, or use the opportunity to demonstrate user-level
modifications/additions to the rules.
